\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Phase 1: Foundations (Weeks 1\'963)\
You cannot design a data system without these. Interviewers test them indirectly in every question \'97 if your fundamentals are shaky, every subsequent answer leaks.\
Week 1: The Vocabulary of Scale\
\
Latency vs throughput vs bandwidth \'97 precise definitions, why confusing them costs you the interview\
Back-of-the-envelope estimation \'97 powers of 2, powers of 10, time conversions (seconds in a day, etc.)\
QPS / RPS math \'97 how to estimate from DAU, MAU, and user behavior\
Storage estimation \'97 rows \'d7 bytes \'d7 retention \'d7 replication\
Drill-heavy week. I'll make you estimate Swiggy's order QPS, Hotstar's bandwidth during IPL finals, PhonePe's transaction storage per year.\
\
Week 2: Distributed Systems Fundamentals\
\
CAP theorem \'97 what it actually says (and the 90% of candidates who get it wrong)\
PACELC \'97 the extension that matters more than CAP in practice\
Consistency models \'97 strong, eventual, causal, read-your-writes, monotonic\
Replication \'97 leader-follower, multi-leader, leaderless\
Partitioning vs sharding \'97 range, hash, consistent hashing\
The fallacies of distributed computing\
\
Week 3: Storage Fundamentals\
\
OLTP vs OLAP \'97 why you can't run analytics on your production Postgres\
Row stores vs column stores \'97 and why Parquet/ORC exist\
B-trees vs LSM trees \'97 when each wins (Postgres vs Cassandra intuition)\
Indexing basics \'97 primary, secondary, covering, composite\
File formats: CSV \uc0\u8594  JSON \u8594  Avro \u8594  Parquet \u8594  ORC \'97 trade-offs and when each fits\
\
\
Phase 2: Data Engineering Core (Weeks 4\'967)\
This is where DE system design diverges from generic backend system design. Most candidates from QA/backend backgrounds underweight this phase and fail interviews on data modeling questions.\
Week 4: Batch Processing & Data Warehouses\
\
Batch processing mental model \'97 when latency in hours is acceptable\
MapReduce \uc0\u8594  Spark \'97 why Spark won, RDD \u8594  DataFrame \u8594  Dataset\
Data warehouse architecture \'97 Snowflake, BigQuery, Redshift internals\
Dimensional modeling \'97 star schema, snowflake schema, fact vs dimension tables\
Slowly Changing Dimensions (SCD Type 1, 2, 3) \'97 interviewers love SCD2\
Real example: how Flipkart models order analytics\
\
Week 5: Stream Processing & Kafka Deep-Dive\
\
Batch vs stream vs micro-batch \'97 when to pick which\
Kafka architecture \'97 brokers, topics, partitions, consumer groups, ISR\
Partitioning strategies \'97 why your partition key choice can sink the design\
